thread.title: $A briefly spikes after Fed decision

title: $A briefly spikes after Fed decision
text:
Fri, Sep 18, 2015, 1:24 PM AEST - Australia Markets close in 2 hrs 36 mins $A briefly spikes after Fed decision AAP â€“ 32 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar is virtually unchanged as it becomes increasingly clear that the Federal Reserve is going to raise its interest rate some time this year. 
At 1200 AEST on Friday, the currency was trading at 71.84 US cents, a touch down from 71.85 cents on Thursday. 
Early on Friday morning, it briefly spiked at 72.76 US cents, its highest level since August 24, after the Federal Reserve kept its interest rate unchanged, but then moved lower. 
Fed chair Janet Yellen cited worries about the slowdown in China as the reason why there wasn't a rate rise this week but added that the US economy continues to grow moderately and there will be an increase before the end of the year. 
"Investors are growing increasingly circumspect of the Fed's position as a delay," FXCM chief currency strategist John Kicklighter said. 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* 71.84 US cents, from 71.85 cents on Thursday 
* 86.23 Japanese yen, from 86.82 yen 
* 63.00 euro cents, from 63.57 euro cents 
* 112.99 New Zealand cents, from 113.14 NZ cents 
* 46.14 British pence, from 46.35 pence 
Government bond yields: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.891pct, from 1.966pct on Thursday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.836pct, from 2.939pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* The December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.200 (implying a yield of 2.800 per cent), up from 97.095 (2.905 per cent) on Thursday. 
The December 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.090 (2.910 per cent), up from 98.010 (1.990 per cent). 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session, bond market closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
